[1]
Date: 12 Nov 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New York Times [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/12/international/europe/12FORM.html>

German Company Admits Defect in Infant Food
------------------------
After the deaths of 2 Israeli children because of a severe vitamin
deficiency, the German manufacturer of infant formula admitted Tuesday that
a kosher, soy-based product it sells in Israel was missing an ingredient
necessary to sustain infant life.
The company, Humana Milchunion, which is based in Everswinkel, Germany,
said that because of human error its Remedia Super Soya 1 product, which is
popular in Israel and Jewish communities elsewhere because of its strict
kosher certification, contained only a fraction of the Vitamin B-1, also
known as thiamine, that is needed to prevent diseases like beri-beri, which
can be fatal in infants.
"This is a one-time sequence of unfortunate circumstances," said Albert
Grosse Frie, spokesman for the Humana Milchunion's board, in a statement
published on the company's Web site.
The Israeli police said Monday that they had begun an investigation of the
matter. "We are investigating the circumstances of the deaths of the babies
and the lack of vitamin B-1 in the cans of formula," said a police
spokesman, Ofir Sivan. "The entire issue is under investigation."
Humana, which said Monday it was investigating the case, added that tests
had shown that the product contained between 29 and 37 micrograms of
vitamin B-1 per 100 grams, less than 1/10 of the advertised amount.
"These values are significantly lower than the product's declared value of
385 micrograms per 100 grams of prepared food," a statement issued by
Humana said. "They are also below the European Union guideline value of 120
micrograms per 100 grams of food."
Humana traced the error to faulty analyses of 2 forerunners to the Super
Soya 1 product, which led to an incorrect assumption that supplemental
levels of thiamine were unnecessary. "Because of an omission in the
procedural checks, the independent analysis was not carried out fully," it
said.
The Humana formula is sold in Israel by Remedia Ltd., which is a subsidiary
of H. J. Heinz.
The Israeli police raided the offices of Remedia in Tel Aviv on Monday
after the Justice Ministry announced a criminal investigation into the
deaths of 2 children because of severe vitamin B-1 deficiency.
[Byline: Richard Bernstein]
