[3]
Date: 12 Nov 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Forbers/ Reuters [edited]
<http://www.forbes.com/home_europe/newswire/2003/11/12/rtr1144640.html>

German prosecutors open probe on Israel baby food
------------------
German prosecutors said on Wednesday they were investigating the makers of
a baby food formula at the centre of an Israeli probe into the deaths of 2
babies.
Prosecutors in the western city of Bielefeld said they opened
investigations after Humana GmbH, makers of baby formula Remedia Super Soya
1, said on Tuesday the product was deficient in vitamin B-1, which is vital
for maintaining infant health.
A spokesman for prosecutors said they were investigating the company on
preliminary suspicions of causing death through negligence as well as
breaches of food safety laws.
He said the German probe, which follows a separate investigation by Israeli
police and at least 2 private lawsuits, was focusing on 3 company executives.
"The investigation has been opened into the head of product development,
the head of quality control and the laboratory chemist on the basis of
their company positions," he said.
The move came as the North Rhine-Westphalia state consumer protection
ministry said it was extending testing on Humana products to cover the
company's entire product range.
A Humana spokesman confirmed that the investigations were taking place and
said the company would cooperate fully. He said Humana was likely to make
personnel changes and may need to make improvements in its quality management.
"You can be sure that there will be personnel changes at the beginning of
next week," he said.
On Tuesday, Humana, part of the Humana Milchunion, Germany's second largest
producer of milk products, said the kosher Super Soya 1 product
manufactured for the Israeli market had less than 1/10 of the amount of
vitamin B-1 advertised.
Israeli police have already launched an investigation into suspicions that
defects in the product led to a B-1 vitamin deficiency that created acute
health problems in at least 9 babies. 2 have died.
The company blamed faulty analyses of previous product recipes and the
failure of procedural checks to spot the error for the lack of vitamin B-1
in the kosher product.
One family in Israel has filed a lawsuit in a Tel Aviv court seeking $230
million in damages and naming Humana and the Israeli Health Ministry. A
separate suit was filed by another Israeli family for some $26 million in
compensation.
A lack of vitamin B-1 can cause a disease called beriberi, characterised by
inflammatory or degenerative changes to the nerves, digestive system and heart.
--
